isciplines to add new insights. Beyond the Latino World War II Hero focuses on home-front issues and government relations, delving into new arenas of research and incorporating stirring oral histories. These recollections highlight realities such as post-traumatic stress disorder and its effects on veterans' families, as well as Mexican American women of this era, whose fighting spirit inspired their daughters to participate in Chicana/o activism of the 1960s and 1970s. Other topics include the importance of radio as a powerful medium during the war and postwar periods, the participation of Mexican nationals in World War II, and intergovernmental negotiations involving Mexico and Puerto Rico. Addressing the complexity of the Latino war experience, such as the tandem between the frontline and the disruption of the agricultural migrant stream on the home front, the authors and contributors unite diverse perspectives to harness the rich resources of an invaluable oral history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aHispanic American womenxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aHispanic AmericansxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, American. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xParticipation, Hispanic American. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAinslie, Ricardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurbelo, Silvia Álvarez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDel Castillo, Richard Griswold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDomínguez, Daphny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRivas-Rodríguez, Maggie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRivas-Rodríguez, Maggie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vo